Yeah.! Yeah.! Yeah.! Yeah.!

232
00:33:01,759 --> 00:33:05,627
There once was a princess
from Siam...

233
00:33:05,696 --> 00:33:09,427
who was sitting here
sort of like I am.

234
00:33:09,500 --> 00:33:15,200
I wined her and dined her,
and then I reclined her.

235
00:33:18,342 --> 00:33:23,905
Ah, shit.
What rhymes with Siam?

236
00:33:23,981 --> 00:33:26,882
That's great.
You make that up?

237
00:33:26,951 --> 00:33:30,717
Pretty obvious, huh?

238
00:33:30,788 --> 00:33:36,055
- That's beautiful.
- No. You're beautiful.

239
00:33:36,127 --> 00:33:39,221
Don't say that.
You pay me.

240
00:33:42,066 --> 00:33:47,094
So, you wanna... you know...

241
00:33:47,171 --> 00:33:49,435
get going?

242
00:33:51,275 --> 00:33:53,835
Sure. Why not?

243
00:34:11,028 --> 00:34:15,692
- How do you miss a hole like that?
- There's my hole! Gotta fly!

244
00:34:15,766 --> 00:34:17,791
Are you blind?

245
00:34:23,941 --> 00:34:27,570
ngel, are you okay?

246
00:34:29,714 --> 00:34:32,877
Ol!

247
00:34:33,918 --> 00:34:36,148
Ol!

248
00:35:02,980 --> 00:35:05,505
You don't wanna watch?

249
00:35:07,218 --> 00:35:09,652
No. Not really.

250
00:35:10,921 --> 00:35:14,254
I don't either.

251
00:35:15,726 --> 00:35:18,820
Ol!

252
00:35:22,500 --> 00:35:26,061
So, what? They brought you
down here to make you feel better?
Is that it?

253
00:35:28,439 --> 00:35:31,408
Yes. Sort of.

254
00:35:31,475 --> 00:35:34,603
Those guys, they think
everything is fixed with a party.

255
00:35:37,148 --> 00:35:40,208
I'm sorry. Who are you?

256
00:35:40,284 --> 00:35:44,345
Oh. Marcela Zabala.

257
00:35:47,224 --> 00:35:51,923
My sister, Isabella,
she's married...
No. No, no. I know.

258
00:35:51,996 --> 00:35:55,932
Nice to meet you. Charles.
Mucho gusto.

259
00:36:09,313 --> 00:36:12,146
So, do you feel better?

260
00:36:17,221 --> 00:36:21,658
No. No, not really.

261
00:36:22,960 --> 00:36:26,657
No. How could you?

262
00:36:26,731 --> 00:36:29,598
With something like that.

263
00:37:02,566 --> 00:37:06,593
Come on, buddy. Wake up.

264
00:37:06,670 --> 00:37:09,332
Come on.

265
00:37:18,716 --> 00:37:22,812
- Did I lose?
- Oh, no. You clobbered him.

266
00:37:26,524 --> 00:37:28,992
Easy.

267
00:37:29,059 --> 00:37:31,687
Easy, easy.
Nice and slow.
I'm fine. I'm fine.

268
00:37:31,762 --> 00:37:33,753
Come on. Let me
buy you some turtle soup.
I'm fine, George.

269
00:37:33,831 --> 00:37:37,824
Go win yourself a race or something.
Let's go down to Sloan's,
and we'll just...

270
00:37:37,902 --> 00:37:42,464
I'm fine, George.
I don't need your help, and I sure
as shit don't need your charity.

271
00:37:44,809 --> 00:37:48,074
Leave me alone,
all right?

272
00:37:53,150 --> 00:37:57,678
It's been 20 years
since I've been on a horse.
Don't worry.

273
00:37:57,755 --> 00:38:00,986
It's the kind of thing
that comes right back.

274
00:38:21,111 --> 00:38:23,375
Let's go.

275
00:38:30,688 --> 00:38:34,055
Come on!

276
00:39:15,432 --> 00:39:18,060
What? She got you back up on a horse,
and now you wanna buy 'em?

277
00:39:18,135 --> 00:39:22,572
Yeah. Maybe. Maybe a couple.
You wanna win or just own 'em?

278
00:39:22,640 --> 00:39:25,666
I wanna win.
What sort of question is that?

279
00:39:25,743 --> 00:39:28,576
Well, you're gonna
need a trainer before
you buy horses.

280
00:39:28,646 --> 00:39:31,740
No. You need two.
So you can fire one, eh?

281
00:39:36,320 --> 00:39:40,256
Randy Thatcher's barn.
Trains about 50 or 60 ponies.

282
00:39:40,324 --> 00:39:45,557
Good fella too.
Real horse person.
A real horse-shitter. Scusa.

283
00:39:45,629 --> 00:39:48,996
Now, now. I don't know.
Maybe you want a smaller barn,
somebody who can take the time to...

284
00:39:49,066 --> 00:39:53,093
Who's that?
- Huh?

285
00:39:53,170 --> 00:39:57,834
Oh, he's a crackpot.
Lives alone in the bushes.

286
00:39:57,908 --> 00:40:00,604
What's he do?

287
00:40:00,678 --> 00:40:06,378
I don't know. He used
to be a trainer, farrier. Now he just
looks after that horse.

288
00:40:07,751 --> 00:40:11,016
Come on.
Let's look at another barn.

289
00:40:27,871 --> 00:40:31,602
- Howdy.
- Hello.

290
00:40:35,879 --> 00:40:40,043
Wh... You hungry?
No. No, thanks.

291
00:40:40,117 --> 00:40:43,109
I'm fine.
Charles Howard.

292
00:40:43,187 --> 00:40:46,350
Tom... Smith.
Nice to meet you, Tom.

293
00:40:49,159 --> 00:40:52,754
What's... What's in his bandage?

294
00:40:54,665 --> 00:41:00,103
Oh, that's hawthorn root.
It increases circulation.

295
00:41:00,170 --> 00:41:03,970
You wanna sit down?

296
00:41:04,041 --> 00:41:07,033
Oh. All right.
Thank you.

297
00:41:10,748 --> 00:41:14,206
Will he get better?

298
00:41:14,284 --> 00:41:17,344
Already is... a little.

299
00:41:17,421 --> 00:41:21,858
Will he race?

300
00:41:21,925 --> 00:41:25,656
No. Not that one.

301
00:41:26,864 --> 00:41:30,391
So why are you fixing him?

302
00:41:30,467 --> 00:41:32,560
'Cause I can.

303
00:41:36,273 --> 00:41:39,868
Every horse
is good for somethin'.

304
00:41:39,943 --> 00:41:43,970
He could be a cart horse
or a lead pony.

305
00:41:44,048 --> 00:41:47,108
And he's still nice to look at.

306
00:41:47,184 --> 00:41:51,644
You know, you don't
throw a whole life away...

307
00:41:51,722 --> 00:41:54,316
just 'cause
he's banged up a little.

308
00:42:08,072 --> 00:42:11,007
Is that coffee?

309
00:42:11,075 --> 00:42:13,066
Yeah.

310
00:42:17,514 --> 00:42:21,280
It's bad, though.

311
00:42:21,552 --> 00:42:24,020
You always tell the truth?

312
00:42:24,088 --> 00:42:27,148
Well, I try to.

313
00:42:42,272 --> 00:42:46,675
It ain't just the speed.
It's the heart.

314
00:42:46,744 --> 00:42:50,771
You want something
that's not afraid to compete.

315
00:42:50,848 --> 00:42:54,545
Half these horses
are just show ponies.

316
00:42:54,618 --> 00:42:58,019
You want something
that's not gonna run from a fight.

317
00:42:59,289 --> 00:43:02,952
How do you find that?

318
00:43:03,026 --> 00:43:06,621
Look, I won the Robles Handicap.
I was second in the Tijuana Derby.

319
00:43:06,697 --> 00:43:09,791
I won the Manzanita Oaks.
You know, that used to be a stakes race.

320
00:43:09,867 --> 00:43:13,530
I know.
I would've won T.J.,
but the piece of shit lugged out on me.

321
00:43:13,604 --> 00:43:18,974
- Sounds great. We'll let ya know.
- Look. I can work 'em out in the morning.

322
00:43:19,042 --> 00:43:24,344
Or even hot-walk 'em
if you need me to.

323
00:43:24,414 --> 00:43:28,077
Really? You'll hot-walk 'em?

324
00:43:28,152 --> 00:43:31,417
This is somethin' else.

325
00:43:31,488 --> 00:43:33,888
A dream come true,
walkin' you around.

326
00:43:33,957 --> 00:43:38,519
Hook you up to a plow,
pull me around for a little while.
Come on.

327
00:43:38,595 --> 00:43:42,725
You ever run in the money?
Huh?

328
00:43:42,800 --> 00:43:45,769
Hey. Hey.
You ever run in the money?

329
00:43:45,836 --> 00:43:49,772
I don't think so. Couldn't beat
a human being, let alone another horse.

330
00:43:49,840 --> 00:43:54,743
You goddamn sack-of-crap
old plater.

331
00:43:54,812 --> 00:43:59,306
Probably the fastest
you're gonna run in your entire life,
you piece-of-shit old glue-pot.

332
00:43:59,383 --> 00:44:03,342
- That's right.

333
00:44:20,871 --> 00:44:26,036
The first time
he saw Seabiscuit, the colt was walking
through the fog at 5:00 in the morning.

334
00:44:27,511 --> 00:44:31,572
Smith would say later that the horse
looked right through him...

335
00:44:31,648 --> 00:44:34,913
as if to say,
"What the hell are you looking at?

336
00:44:34,985 --> 00:44:39,820
- Who do you think you are?"

337
00:44:39,890 --> 00:44:42,654
He was a small horse,
barely 15 hands.

338
00:44:42,726 --> 00:44:47,493
He was hurting too.
There was a limp in his walk,

339
00:44:47,564 --> 00:44:51,091
a wheezing when he breathed.

340
00:44:51,168 --> 00:44:53,728
Smith didn't pay attention
to that.

341
00:44:53,804 --> 00:44:58,468
He was looking the horse
in the eye.

342
00:44:58,542 --> 00:45:02,342
God... damn.

343
00:45:08,518 --> 00:45:13,114
He was the son of Hard Tack,
sired by the mighty Man O' War.

344
00:45:13,190 --> 00:45:16,956
But the breeding did little
to impress anyone at Claiborne Farms.

345
00:45:17,027 --> 00:45:19,928
Get rid of him.

346
00:45:24,201 --> 00:45:28,968
At six months,
he was shipped off to train with
the legendary trainer Sunny Fitzsimmons,

347
00:45:29,039 --> 00:45:32,770
who, over time,
developed a similar opinion of the colt.

348
00:45:32,843 --> 00:45:36,609
Is that a racehorse
or a lead pony?

349
00:45:37,814 --> 00:45:41,045
The judgment wasn't helped
by his gentle nature.

350
00:45:41,118 --> 00:45:45,851
Where his sire had been a fierce,
almost violent competitor,

351
00:45:45,923 --> 00:45:48,892
Seabiscuit took to sleeping
for huge chunks of the day...

352
00:45:48,959 --> 00:45:54,158
and enjoyed lolling for hours
under the boughs of the juniper trees.

353
00:45:54,231 --> 00:45:57,792
His other great talent was eating.

354
00:45:57,868 --> 00:46:03,238
Though half the size of other colts,
Seabiscuit could frequently
eat twice as much.

355
00:46:04,541 --> 00:46:07,567
Fitzsimmons decided
the horse was lazy...

356
00:46:07,644 --> 00:46:11,239
and felt sure he could train
the obstinance out of him.

357
00:46:11,315 --> 00:46:15,752
I want you to hit him
as many times as you can
over a quarter of a mile.

358
00:46:15,819 --> 00:46:20,188
When he didn't improve,
they decided the colt
was incorrigible.

359
00:46:22,125 --> 00:46:24,616
They made him a training partner
to better horses,

360
00:46:24,695 --> 00:46:27,186
forcing him to lose
head-to-head duels...

361
00:46:27,264 --> 00:46:29,630
to boost the confidence
of the other animal.

362
00:46:30,934 --> 00:46:32,868
By the time
he was three years old,

363
00:46:32,936 --> 00:46:36,394
Seabiscuit was struggling
in two cheap claiming races a week.

364
00:46:37,841 --> 00:46:42,175
Soon he grew as bitter and angry
as his sire Hard Tack had been.

365
00:46:44,648 --> 00:46:48,084
He was sold
for the rock-bottom price
of $2,000.

366
00:46:52,022 --> 00:46:54,752
And, of course,
it all made sense.

367
00:46:54,825 --> 00:46:58,625
Champions were large,
they were sleek,

368
00:46:58,695 --> 00:47:00,686
they were without imperfection.

369
00:47:02,165 --> 00:47:06,124
When they finally did race him,
he did just what
they had trained him to do.

370
00:47:06,203 --> 00:47:08,137
He lost.

371
00:47:10,574 --> 00:47:12,508
What exactly
is it you like?

372
00:47:12,576 --> 00:47:15,602
He's got spirit.

373
00:47:15,679 --> 00:47:18,239
I'll say.

374
00:47:19,549 --> 00:47:23,110
Can... Can he be ridden?
Oh, sure.

375
00:47:26,656 --> 00:47:29,716
Eventually.

376
00:47:29,793 --> 00:47:33,729
He can be
a little touchy.
Yeah, I got it.

377
00:47:33,797 --> 00:47:36,425
No. Really.

378
00:47:36,500 --> 00:47:38,491
I'm fine.

379
00:47:47,244 --> 00:47:49,712
Jesus Christ!
That horse is nuts!

380
00:48:08,131 --> 00:48:11,100
Come on.!
Come on.! Come on.!

381
00:48:11,168 --> 00:48:13,136
Let's go.! Come on,
you sons of bitches.!

382
00:48:25,015 --> 00:48:27,074
Let's go.!
Come on.!

383
00:48:29,252 --> 00:48:31,186
Let's go! Come on,
you sons of bitches!

384
00:48:31,254 --> 00:48:33,984
I'll take all of you!
Come on! Come on!

385
00:48:58,315 --> 00:49:01,216
It's okay.

386
00:49:02,919 --> 00:49:06,047
- I'm not afraid of you.

387
00:49:06,123 --> 00:49:09,115
Sure. I know.

388
00:49:10,660 --> 00:49:13,754
I know what
you're all about.

389
00:49:21,171 --> 00:49:23,105
You hungry?

390
00:49:25,475 --> 00:49:27,466
Huh?

391
00:49:29,913 --> 00:49:32,677
Yeah. Bet you are.

392
00:49:33,750 --> 00:49:37,413
Huh? Come on.

393
00:49:37,487 --> 00:49:39,478
Come on, boy.

394
00:49:48,765 --> 00:49:51,256
Yeah.

395
00:49:55,338 --> 00:49:58,466
Why don't you just
breeze him around
one turn.

396
00:49:58,542 --> 00:50:01,204
Give the folks a look.
Right.

397
00:50:02,646 --> 00:50:06,138
Red Pollard,
Mr. And Mrs. Howard.
Yeah. Hi.

398
00:50:06,216 --> 00:50:09,652
Hello.

399
00:50:09,719 --> 00:50:11,653
Well, we'll just
be movin' on.

400
00:50:17,561 --> 00:50:19,688
Does he breeze?

401
00:50:19,763 --> 00:50:22,163
Well, we'll find out.

402
00:50:40,951 --> 00:50:43,511
Seems pretty fast.
Yeah.

403
00:50:43,587 --> 00:50:45,612
In every direction.

404
00:50:47,524 --> 00:50:50,220
Hell, he's so beat up,
it's hard to tell what he's like.

405
00:50:51,394 --> 00:50:53,692
I just can't help feelin'
they got him...

406
00:50:53,763 --> 00:50:56,323
so screwed up
runnin'in a circle,

407
00:50:56,399 --> 00:51:00,358
he's forgotten
what he was born to do.

408
00:51:01,571 --> 00:51:04,734
He just needs to learn
how to be a horse again.

409
00:51:06,409 --> 00:51:08,969
Well, how do
you do that?

410
00:51:16,419 --> 00:51:20,879
How far do you
want me to take him?
Till he stops.

411
00:51:22,325 --> 00:51:24,953
Okay.

412
00:51:25,028 --> 00:51:27,019
That seems like
a pretty good ride.

413
00:51:28,632 --> 00:51:31,533
Hope so.

414
00:51:49,119 --> 00:51:51,053
That's it, boy.

415
00:51:51,121 --> 00:51:53,055
You're all right.

416
00:51:53,123 --> 00:51:55,717
Let's see what you got, boy.
Ha! Ha!

417
00:51:55,792 --> 00:51:59,250
Ha! Ha! Whoo!

418
00:51:59,329 --> 00:52:02,196
That's it, boy. That's it!

419
00:52:08,305 --> 00:52:10,398
Yeah!

420
00:52:17,113 --> 00:52:19,411
Whoo!

421
00:52:23,019 --> 00:52:25,010
Whoo-hoo!

422
00:52:33,863 --> 00:52:37,390
Well, at least
he wasn't expensive.
No. That's true.

423
00:52:40,470 --> 00:52:43,837
Whoo!

424
00:52:48,378 --> 00:52:51,245
Goddamn it!
You're an amazing animal!

425
00:52:55,552 --> 00:52:58,851
Whoo!

426
00:53:18,174 --> 00:53:20,165
You can
come inside, you know.

427
00:53:20,243 --> 00:53:23,440
I'm fine. Thank you.
Yeah,
you look it.

428
00:53:25,181 --> 00:53:27,206
No, really, I'm fine.

429
00:53:28,284 --> 00:53:31,219
Okay.
Suit yourself.

430
00:53:43,233 --> 00:53:45,292
Welcome.

431
00:53:59,249 --> 00:54:01,843
Thank you.
You're welcome.

432
00:54:13,196 --> 00:54:15,187
It's okay.

433
00:54:16,266 --> 00:54:18,200
Oh, I'm not that hungry.

434
00:54:18,268 --> 00:54:20,896
Mmm. Sure you're not.

435
00:54:22,172 --> 00:54:24,106
It's just a lot of food.

436
00:54:29,379 --> 00:54:31,904
It's okay.

437
00:54:31,981 --> 00:54:34,347
Rather have you strong than thin.

438
00:54:58,041 --> 00:55:00,168
They called it "relief,"

439
00:55:00,243 --> 00:55:02,108
but it was
a lot more than that.

440
00:55:02,178 --> 00:55:04,408
It had dozens of names:

441
00:55:04,481 --> 00:55:06,972
N.R.A., W.P.A.,

442
00:55:07,050 --> 00:55:09,484
the C.C.C.

443
00:55:09,552 --> 00:55:12,316
But it really came down
to just one thing.

444
00:55:14,624 --> 00:55:17,092
For the first time
in a long time,

445
00:55:17,160 --> 00:55:19,151
someone cared.

446
00:55:20,497 --> 00:55:23,660
For the first time
in a long time,

447
00:55:23,733 --> 00:55:26,224
you were no longer alone.

448
00:57:10,640 --> 00:57:13,302
Goat racing?

449
00:57:13,376 --> 00:57:17,312
Oh, no. Just trying
to calm him down a little.

450
00:57:17,380 --> 00:57:20,247
Smart ones
hate being alone
all the time.

451
00:57:20,316 --> 00:57:23,149
Oh.
And sometimes
another animal,

452
00:57:23,219 --> 00:57:26,188
it just...
just soothes them a bit.

453
00:58:04,994 --> 00:58:07,394
Pretty quiet in there.

454
00:58:07,463 --> 00:58:10,057
What'd you do?

455
00:58:10,133 --> 00:58:12,124
Go take a look.

456
00:58:19,942 --> 00:58:23,605
Oh.

457
00:58:23,680 --> 00:58:28,583
# Rock of ages, cleft for me #

458
00:58:28,651 --> 00:58:33,645
# I am hid and safe in thee #

459
00:58:33,723 --> 00:58:38,660
# For the water
and the blood #

460
00:58:38,861 --> 00:58:40,795
# From thy riven...#

461
00:58:40,863 --> 00:58:43,058
Okay. You don't
break him or anything,

462
00:58:43,132 --> 00:58:46,158
but we gotta see
what he's got.

463
00:58:46,235 --> 00:58:49,363
You take him
to the 5  pole...

464
00:58:49,439 --> 00:58:51,771
and turn him loose.

465
00:58:51,841 --> 00:58:54,935
Turn him loose?
Yeah, son.

466
00:58:55,011 --> 00:58:57,002
He's a racehorse.

467
00:59:01,117 --> 00:59:03,517
Ha! Ha!
Come on!

468
00:59:10,460 --> 00:59:12,052
Come on!

469
00:59:12,128 --> 00:59:16,189
Ha! Come on!
I know you got more than this!
Let's show 'em, boy!

470
00:59:21,070 --> 00:59:23,004
How's he look?

471
00:59:23,072 --> 00:59:25,199
Asleep.

472
00:59:26,375 --> 00:59:30,243
Come on!
Let's show 'em, Pops!
Come on!

473
00:59:40,022 --> 00:59:43,583
Whoo! There it is! Yeah!
Whoo!

474
00:59:43,659 --> 00:59:45,820
Oh, my.

475
00:59:57,140 --> 00:59:59,836
Yeah, you and me! Let's go!

476
00:59:59,909 --> 01:00:01,604
Whoo! Whoo-hoo!

